##To get masks for the home hospital

Wechat, boyangcongpeople

The function introduces, peels off the human shell, records the real sensible life. Presented by the in-depth Reporting Department of the Beijing News.

Volunteers deliver the supplies they receive to hospital staff. Photo courtesy of the respondents

By Han Qinke, Beijing News

Editor | Jing Yi Wang proofread | Xu Li Yang

The text is about 2,828 words long and takes about five minutes to read

Had it not been for the outbreak, Cheng did not expect to be able to join a wechat group called "help buy masks. ".

Cheng is from Jianshi County, in the southwestern province of Hubei, which is part of the Enshi Tujia and Miao Autonomous Prefecture and has a population of about half a million. Unlike the oft-reported cities of Wuhan, Huanggang and Xiaogan, Jianshi County has received little outside attention. However, hospitals here also face shortages.

On January 19, Cheng returned home from his job in Shanghai and began helping his hometown hospital raise money. In her material coordination group, 14 volunteers are responsible for material docking, information collation, logistics assistance, financial assistance, clerical assistance and so on. Most of the members are scattered across the country and had not known each other before. Now, the team is working at high speed towards a common goal: the Foshan Mask.

"To help my family back home. "

When Cheng returned to Jianshi County on January 19, locals were not yet aware of the severity of the outbreak and most were not wearing face masks. Cheng Yu to his parents to do work, "advised them to wear a mask advised for 3 days. ".

News of the epidemic spread in waves. On January 23, Wuhan closed the Han corridor. Then, the news of the shortage of supplies in Hubei's major hospitals hit the news screen on friends'circles, and the number of people wearing masks in the county suddenly increased.

At the same time, Cheng Yu learned that the county people's hospital protective supplies also appeared in short supply. A friend at the hospital complained to her, "that the front-line doctors are almost out of N95 masks, can only wear ordinary masks, lack of protective clothing, also lack of disinfectant. " She decided to do something for her hometown.

Cheng Yu contacted several hospitals in the county, asked for supplies, and then released information to friends circle, looking for sources, Verification Qualifications, fund-raising procurement, contact logistics... she never engaged in similar work began to try.

Initially, Cheng Yu posted the help-seeking message to his friends'circle to ask them to forward it, without expecting too much. Surprisingly, not long after the launch, a number of individuals and organizations with materials expressed their intention to donate.

Living in Japan, Lin Ya reached out to Cheng Yu.

Lin Ya, 39, a native of Fujian Province, has lived in Japan for 15 years. Following the news that health care workers in Hubei were in urgent need of protective equipment, she and more than 140 Chinese in Japan formed a purchasing group for protective equipment. They bought masks in stores in Tokyo, Ōsaka, Niigata and Shizuoka, Japan, and sent them home.

"The hospitals in Wuhan have already allocated a lot of materials, so we want to send them to places around Hubei that are in short supply, " Lin said, referring to the donation to Jianshi County

Every day, Lin Ya to spend most of the day to all kinds of convenience stores, drug stores, shopping malls purchase masks, "buy the best protective effect, regardless of price. ". With face masks running out in the city, she had to ride for more than an hour, carrying her one-year-old on her back, to the suburbs and the countryside in search of masks. It takes more time to find a mask than to buy one.

Linya's prices are a little higher because it's hard to order directly from factories because of tight supply, but many Japanese retailers have cut prices to support Wuhan, which has made her feel especially warm.

The purchase cost her more than 400,000 yen, or nearly 30,000 yuan, and she donated 185 N95 masks, 1,084 normal masks, 2,000 disposable caps, 107 goggles and 900 medical gloves to Cheng Yu for free. Her oldest son, 14, and her second son, 9, often asked her, "why do we have so much stuff? Why do we do this? " Her answer echoed Ms. Cheng's original, "to help family back home. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Lin Ya from Japan sent goods, above the stick "the motherland refueling. ". Photo courtesy of the respondents

"almost half an expert. "

Nearly half a month since, many know do not know friends contact Cheng Yu, hope to join. So far, Cheng Yu's small team has a total of 14 volunteers, from finance, clothing, medical beauty and other industries.

To help the front-line staff save time, the volunteers decided to do part of the screening, identifying the type of mask and determining whether it could be used for clinical protection. "We tried to find the business license and medical license of each mask brand to reassure the hospital. Those who did not always suggested that they use them as disposable masks for general departments, " Cheng said.

Because everyone had a general lack of understanding of medical protection supplies, can only do while learning, "has been complementary knowledge, are almost half an expert. " Cheng Yuxiao said.

At present, home-made medical protective products can be queried through the website of the State Drug Administration. If you input the name, you can find the scope of application and the intended use of the related products, but the materials from abroad, volunteers are also required to translate and compare search criteria through the official website.

The volunteer, Yang Hao, is a finance professional who does most of the screening. After receiving the materials, he needs to know the standard of protective equipment, inquire the quality standard, check the test report. "starting with search engines, look at the websites of various manufacturers of protective products for product categories and application scenarios, " said Yang Hao, who spends hours a day searching through countless pages of information.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Standard checklist of protective equipment used by the volunteers. Photo courtesy of the respondents

Now, volunteers have learned all kinds of masks. At the end of January, a factory in Dongguan said it had a shipment of masks. "It's an industrial-grade N95, and it can't be used by doctors, " Cheng said. The manufacturer's failure to offer a purchase contract was another reason for her refusal. In her view, the failure to provide materials for purchase contracts meant that the channels were not clear and reselling was not ruled out. "You can't let enthusiasm be exploited, and you can't make trouble for the hospital, " she said.

Donors are also helping to share the work. Each time before sending masks and other supplies, Lin Ya will be dedicated to the use of a variety of materials to send Cheng Yu pictures. In order to screen information, Cheng Yu's work group also specifically sought out three volunteers who understood Japanese.

Solving one problem after another

Get up at 7 am, go to bed at 1 am, except to go to the toilet, other time is in contact with all kinds of people and information... describe the current situation, Cheng Yu felt that he was "working overtime" every day, "I didn't have time to have a good meal during the Spring Festival. "

But what really bothered her was the difficulty of raising supplies.

They have ordered masks from manufacturers in Xiantao, Hubei Province, and other provinces and cities, but most of the time they have not been able to return because of excessive national demand. Some manufacturers even took their orders, and then backtracked temporarily, sold the materials to other institutions. They have to keep reaching out to more suppliers and donors.

How to send the masks back to Jianshi County is a new problem. Lin said the Japanese embassy opened a green channel to send parcels to Wuhan, but the parcels can not continue to transit after arriving in Wuhan. Part of the usual international express because of orders to Hubei too many and no longer accept new parcel orders. Eventually, she had to send the mask to Shanghai via SF, and from Shanghai to Jianshi County.

After five days, the first batch of 1,000 Japanese medical-grade masks donated by Lin Ya arrived in Jianshi County on February 2. Within two hours of the arrival of the supplies, the volunteers had delivered the masks to the Jianshi County People's Hospital and the Jianshi County Hospital of Traditional Chinese medicine in the rain.

Volunteers are also working to open up more transit corridors. They set up transshipment points in Beijing, Shanghai, Hangzhou and Chongqing, through which goods can be transshipped back to the start of construction. Fast is the only criterion in the selection of the mode of transport.

"The roads are all closed, so it's really difficult to transport, " said Yang Hao, who said he was trying to separate large packages or send supplies to Chongqing and bring them back by car. "We are trying to have a car on each side to hand over supplies at the border, " says Jianshi County, which borders Chongqing

In this process, the kindness and enthusiasm shown by many parties is the motive force that Sustains Cheng Yu people to continue.

Lin Ya's home in Tokyo is the "Distribution Center" of the Japanese love purchasing group. Members from all over the world will send the masks they buy to Lin Ya's home for temporary storage. As the number of packages grew, she had to vacate her basement to store masks.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Medical and protective materials stacked in Lin Ya's home. Photo courtesy of the respondent

The volunteers are still receiving donations. So far, they have received donations from 73 people, totaling more than 50,000 yuan. In the fund-raising Group, the volunteers publish donation details, as well as the time, product, quantity, amount and waybill number of each purchase, for external reference. All the funds raised were used for the procurement of standard medical and protective supplies.

Their efforts have to some extent alleviated the shortage of hospital materials. On February 2, a Jianshi County Hospital procurement staff told the Beijing News that the current shortage of common face masks and disinfectants in the hospital has slightly improved, "The county anti-epidemic headquarters and the people who care for the disease have provided some of the materials, and the volunteers have really paid a lot in helping to dock the materials. "

At 3 am on February 1, Cheng Yu finally lay in bed after a tiring day. "I know I'm small and I know I'm limited, but isn't it a relief to be able to do what I can? " She posted in her circle of friends
